And when we're facing down the most dire threat humanity had faced, the time for testing focuses is over.And I think a lot of science teachers would rally behind this paradigm change. We generally love teaching meaningful science, and this is it.

And if there's an economic push towards it, i/e a spike in green jobs, I think that will be a huge driver. But we need the curriculum to focus on implementing solutions, not just test scores, as the time for testing is over. Education's purpose is to prepare kids for the world.

Is this something that could happen? Maybe. We're starting to see the awful effects of things tied to science dominating our lives. Virology went from niche science to mainstream in a few months. As climate disasters continue, it's more likely the demand will increase.

Knowing mitochondria is the powerhouse of the cell is pointless unless you're getting into cell biology. But it being common knowledge that just planting coniferous trees in x type of soil is a bad idea, now that's useful.

We need a new science ed curriculum that focuses on understanding complex models and ecology. We need it to be not tied to testing, and led by educators, not billionaires or rocket scientists. We need to give kids tools to work with this, so they have hope for their future.

So we have a 60 year old curriculum to win the space race being taught to kids using a 30 year old testing paradigm by burnt out teachers and kids facing a climate disaster, being unequipped to handle it.

Now, flip to the 90s. You have people like Gates and Buffet deciding that the US needs to win the testing race, comparing the US testing scores to countries with dual tracks (who don't test the trade job track students.) Again, teachers weren't really part of this decision.

Pre-1960s, science ed was largely practical. It involved a lot of stuff on repairing things, gardening, etc. But when Sputnik happened, the US government decided to refocus science curriculum towards hard science to win the space race. No teachers were part of this decision.

Specifically, #science #education. While rethinking all areas of education is important, science is critical, and it requires completely switching educational paradigms. But to understand that, bit of a history lesson. #sciencetwitter

@AnnemiekeMilks I've used the past to help people face the future & thinking about solutions. They can be a mixture of traditional approaches & future thinking but it needs to be citizen led as well as by scientists & policy makers.

@AnnemiekeMilks Finally we are good at telling stories about time. In the past & future. We have a role to play in educating, preparing people for what is to come & think innovatively. This is not about creating the past but to help inspire & provide food for thought.
@Tash_Reynolds Agreed

@AnnemiekeMilks Also there are some great materials around soils & crops. Practical aspects around rain fed crops in arid environments - what has worked well & under what conditions? Which recepie worked the best under which future climate system?

@AnnemiekeMilks We can also think about how ecosystems have responded in the past to understand the configurations of what was more resilient to change. For example is a bronze age or Neolithic landscape more resilient? Which mode might serve us better into the future?

@AnnemiekeMilks I think we can offer some solutions, especially in terms of considering flooding - thinking about past pathways of rivers for example & how they will restart with sea level rise & where to place that water. History tells us some good solutions. 1/2

@AnnemiekeMilks Academia *is* inward looking, is often too focused on doing things that are really mainly for other academics and for our own status etc. I have seen some projects focused on climate change that really made me wonder: what is the point of this?! /3

I expect that there's no longer going to be seasonal or regional divisions in preparedness measures and practices.In a jest of a very serious situation: no, sharknado was still not a possibility. This was a fresh water river dive. No sharks to be found in the vicinity.

More and more often, well trained and experienced individuals are going to find themselves in unexpected situations because our environment is throwing this (would have been avoidable) curveballs at us.

Seriously. I've dove in silt and in the dark, in wrecks and with sharks. But getting out of the water and knowing we might have been out there with a tornado? Whole new type of... maybe not fear but, well measured anxiety? This is the reality of a changing climate.

To be entirely honest, I have no clue what the safety concerns for diving in a tornado are? This is an area where tornados where pure myth just a few years ago, and are now having multiple in a summer. We know our safety limits for other weather scenarios. Some how, not tornados.

What started off as a breezy and drizzly day turned into a Tornado Watch and subsequent warning while I was underwater. The threat seemed to pass by the time we surfaced (though come to find out there was in fact one 20 miles away).
